Now suppose, for simplicity, that Y is non-singular, so that \omega _Y^{n-p}= \Omega _Y^{n-p}.
There is a natural homomorphism from \Omega _X^{n-p} to \Omega _Y^{n-p}, whence a canonical section s_Y of the sheaf \mathscr {E} \kern  -1.5pt \mathit {xt} _{ \mathcal {O} _X}^p( \mathcal {O} _Y, \Omega _X^p), that we call, if all the components of Y are of dimension n-p, the fundamental section of the sheaf \mathscr {E} \kern  -1.5pt \mathit {xt} _{ \mathcal {O} _X}^p( \mathcal {O} _Y, \Omega _X^p).
By , this section defines an element of \operatorname {Ext} _{ \mathcal {O} _X}^p(X; \mathcal {O} _Y, \Omega _X^p).
But the natural homomorphism \mathcal {O} _X \to \mathcal {O} _Y defines a homomorphism
